04269nam a22007095i 9780824873943DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024037241  a97808248739437 a10.1515/97808248739432doi  a(DE-B1597)483729  a(OCoLC)608422602  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aLAW0000002bisacsh0483pa340qDE-1011 aMiike, Lawrence H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWater and the Law in Hawaii /cLawrence H. Miike. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tIntroduction -- t1. Aquifers, Streams, and Things -- t2. Hawaiian Mythology and Social Structure -- t3. Land and Water in the Kingdom of Hawai‘i -- t4. Traditional and Customary Rights on Private Property -- t5. Water Law in Hawai‘i -- t6. The Waiähole Ditch Controversy -- t7. Water and the Future -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWater and the Law in Hawaii provides an intellectual and legal framework for understanding both the past and future of Hawai‘i’s freshwater resources. It covers not only the känäwai (laws) governing the balancing act between preservation and use, but also the science of aquifers and streams and the customs and traditions practiced by ancient and present-day Hawaiians on the äina (land) and in the wai (water). In placing Hawaii water law in the context of its historical development, the author condenses an enormous amount of information on traditional Hawaiian social structure and mythology. His analysis and explanation of the Hawaii Supreme Court decisions on water rights pose difficult questions and reveal the Court's at times defective reasoning by referring readers to original source material. He is the first author to explain fully how water use permits will play out in a variety of circumstances that may arise in the future, and he discusses the interrelationship between the State Water Code and the common law on water rights, which few people understand or are aware of. Water and the Law in Hawaii is a vital contribution to understanding water law in Hawaii. It will prove invaluable to students of the subject and will appeal to those with an interest in cultural anthropology, planning, Hawaiian history, and political science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082487394340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824873943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824873943.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK